---
import Layout from '../../../components/layout/Layout.astro';
import ArtworkSchema from '../../../components/seo/ArtworkSchema.astro';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = 'Un mensaje';

const img1 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/un-mensaje/un-mensaje-01.webp')).default;
---

<Layout
  lang={lang}
  title="Un mensaje — Work"
  description="Un mensaje. Installation, Morse code. Maria Elvira Escallon."
>

  <ArtworkSchema
    title="Un mensaje"
    year="date to be confirmed"
    medium="Installation, Morse code"
    description="Installation that uses Morse code as a means to transmit a message."
    url="https://mariaelviraescallon.com/en/works/un-mensaje/"
  />

  <article class="work-page">
    <div class="container">

      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="work-page__header">
        <p class="label">Work / 017</p>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p class="work-page__meta">Date to be confirmed &nbsp;/&nbsp; Installation, Morse code</p>
      </header>

      <!-- Main gallery -->
      <div class="work-page__gallery">
        <img src={img1.src} alt="Un mensaje — Installation, Morse code" loading="eager">
      </div>

      <!-- Text + Technical sheet -->
      <div class="work-page__body">
        <div class="work-page__text">

          <p class="curatorial">
            Related to the artist's interest in minimal communication devices. The work
            uses Morse code as a means to transmit a message, creating a bridge between
            the visible and the invisible, the audible and the silent.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            <em>Un mensaje</em> connects with <em>Las caminantes</em> (2024), where plants
            also emit a message in Morse code. In both works, Morse code functions as a
            minimal device — a form of communication that demands attention and decipherment,
            inviting the viewer to pause and observe.
          </p>

          <h3 style="margin-top: var(--s4);">CONTEXT</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The use of Morse code is recurrent in Escallon's practice. As the artist herself
            describes: her intervention consists of pointing out situations "almost without
            touching, through minimal devices that invite observation — accompanying scenes
            with small Morse code deciphered near the installation." <em>Un mensaje</em>
            takes this strategy to its most essential form.
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="work-page__ficha">
          <h4>TECHNICAL SHEET</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            <strong>Un mensaje</strong><br>
            Date to be confirmed<br><br>
            Installation, Morse code.
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">THEMES</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            Minimal communication<br>
            Morse code<br>
            The visible and the invisible<br>
            Devices for observation
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">RELATED WORKS</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            <a href="/maria-elvira-escallon/en/works/las-caminantes/" style="color: var(--moss); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--paper-dark);">
              Las caminantes (2024)
            </a>
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">HOW TO CITE</h4>
          <div class="ficha" style="font-size: 0.65rem;">
            Escallon, M.E. <em>Un mensaje</em>.
            Installation, Morse code. Available at:
            mariaelviraescallon.com/en/works/un-mensaje/
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>

</Layout>
